Spatial Regression Analysis

Sofie Ditmer and Mie Arnau Martinez

6/4/2021

Description:
This script is developed as part of the exam for the course Cultural Data Science: Spatial Analytics, Autumn 2021 at Aarhus University. The project for the exam is a spatial analysis of the voting pattern at the 2019 UK general election. This script constitutes the spatial regression analysis and includes global regressions, spatial regressions and comparison of the two models residuals through an autocorrelation test to check for spatial clustering.

The reason for this is that a model that captures the spatial features of the data will not show spatial clustering of the model residuals. However, the global model should have spatial clustering if spatial features are present in the data.

So, our hypothesis is that the spatial regression will fit better on our data (lower AIC score) compared to our global model. Furthermore, we hypothesize that the global model residuals will show spatial clustering whereas the spatial model residuals will show random dispersion.

From the first model, we can deduce that percentage of votes on the Conservative Party can be significantly predicted by population density, pubs per inhabitants, average age and average income, F(5, 525) = 141, p < .0001, adjusted R2 = .57. Percentage of white population didnt significantly predict percentage of votes, = 0.11 (SE = 0.31), t = 0.37, p > 0.05. However, all other predictors were significant. So, 57% of the variance in this data seems to be explained by our model.
Lastly, the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) for the model is 1067.76 (this we use to compare the model with GWR).

The overall fit of the model and the model coefficients may vary across space.

We can quickly visualize how our model residuals vary across space.

From the map, there seem to be spatial clustering in the residuals. These effects are especially prominent around urban areas like around Liverpool, Sunderland and Leeds. However, to make sure that the spatial clustering is significant we perform an autocorrelation test.

Before performing the spatial autocorrelation, we have to define neighbors. 

# Define neighbor list (Queen's adjacency neighborhood definition)
nb <- poly2nb(constituency_data)

# Simplify the boundaries to speed up the processing
constituencies_sm <- st_cast(st_simplify(constituency_data, dTolerance = 250), to = "MULTIPOLYGON")

# Define center of constituencies
constituency_centers <- st_coordinates(st_centroid(constituencies_sm$geometry))

# Show the connections
plot(constituencies_sm$geometry); plot(nb, constituency_centers, col = "red", add = TRUE)

# Add weights to each constituency according to distance to its neighbors. We use zero.policy = TRUE because there are islands that do not have any neighbors
lw <- nb2listw(nb, zero.policy = TRUE)


Then, we can perform the autocorrelation test with monte carlo simulation on the model residuals. 

# adding the residuals to the simplified sf data frame
constituencies_sm$global_conservative_lm <- residuals(global_conservative_lm)

# autocorrelation test for the Conservative party
moran.mc(constituencies_sm$global_conservative_lm, lw, 999, zero.policy = TRUE)
## 
##  Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I
## 
## data:  constituencies_sm$global_conservative_lm 
## weights: lw  
## number of simulations + 1: 1000 
## 
## statistic = 0.59568, observed rank = 1000, p-value = 0.001
## alternative hypothesis: greater


From the Morans I test, we deduce that there appears to be spatial clustering of the model residuals, I = 0.60, p = 0.001.

Spatial Regression Analysis:

In geographically weighted regression (GWR), we sort of compromise between a global model (a model across all points in space) and a local model (a model only containing one observation). This is done by modeling across a subset of the data through a bandwidth kernel and weighting the different observations according to how close they are in space to the focal observation. So, we make a regression for each location (constituency) and the model estimates then depend on the location of the observations. This allows us to discern the importance of our predictors at different constituencies in England in relation to how they affect voting patterns.

The bandwidth will be what bias the model in terms of defining the neighbors. Essentially, finding the bandwidth is like asking how many locations should we use to compute the varying slope as we more though the data space? We can choose either that the bandwidth is a given diameter around our focal point or it can be adaptive so that it takes the same number of observations for each focal points. The latter would mean that for denser areas, the bandwidth would be smaller. As our areas vary a lot in density, we choose the latter.

Furthermore, we use a Gaussian kernel function which allows all locations to contribute to the model at focal point. However, nearer locations are weighted higher than distant locations.

As we are using an sf object, we also have to define a set of coordinates for each constituency so we first define the centroids for each constituency. Then, we find the optimal bandwidth for our model on conservative votes. Lastly, we use this to fit the model to the observations.

GWR for Conservative Votes:
First, we perform our spatial analysis on the model on Conservative votes.

# calculate Optimal kernel bandwidth using the constituency coordinates defined when specifying neighborhoods, and adapting the kernel size according to density of areas
bw_conservative <- gwr.sel(perc_votes_conservative ~ pop_density + pubs_per_inhabitant + perc_white_pop + avg_age + avg_income, data = constituency_data, coords = constituency_centroids, adapt = T)

# fitting the model for conservative votes
gwr_model_conservative = gwr(perc_votes_conservative ~ pop_density + pubs_per_inhabitant 
                             + perc_white_pop + avg_age + avg_income, 
                             data = constituency_data, 
                             coords = constituency_centroids, 
                             adapt=bw_conservative, 
                             hatmatrix=TRUE, 
                             se.fit=TRUE, 
                             gweight=gwr.Gauss)

## 
## data:  gwr_conservative_merged$gwr.e 
## weights: lw  
## number of simulations + 1: 1000 
## 
## statistic = 0.12598, observed rank = 1000, p-value = 0.001
## alternative hypothesis: greater

Here, we see that the spatial clustering is still significant but also remarkably less than for the global model. Morans I for the GWR for Conservative votes is 0.13 compared to 0.60 for the global model. However, we should remain cautious when drawing inferences on the basis of the autocorrelation test for the GWR as this is using a different optimization approach.

Here, we see that we get an optimal bandwidth of 18 neighbors. Using this for our model, we improve the adjusted R2 from 66% for the global regression model to 87% for the GWR model. Similarly, the AIC value decreases from 945.19 for the global regression model to 498.41 for the GWR model.

As with the Conservative model, we observe that the spatial clustering is still significant but reduced compared to the global model. Morans I for the GWR for Labour votes is 0.10 compared to 0.52 for the global model.

Based on our spatial regression analysis, we can conclude that the relationship between voting patterns and demographics is sensitive to where you live in England.
So, space mattered to the results of the UK general election in 2019.
